
[1]boom

   BOOM, n. A long pole or spar, run out from various parts of a ship, or
   other vessel, for the purpose of extending the bottom of particular
   sails; as the jib-boom, studding-sail boom, main-boom, square-sail
   boom. &c.

   1. A strong iron chain, fastened to spars, and extended across a river,
   or the mouth of a harbor, to prevent an enemy's ships from passing.

   2. A pole set up as a mark to direct seamen how to keep the channel, in
   shallow water.
